North: merica; Saint Barthélemy in the Caribbean; French Polynesia, New Caledonia, Wallis and Futuna and Clipperton Island in the Pacific Ocean; and finally French Southern and Antarctic Lands The European part of France, called Metropolitan France, extends from the Mediterranean Sea to the English Channel and the
East: French regions, which are the highest level of integration in the French unitary state. Metropolitan regions and overseas regions are often differentiated although they have exactly the same legal status. The main difference between metropolitan and overseas regions is a reduced value-added tax in the overseas regions to offset the higher cost of imports.
Metropolitan regions: comprising the European territory of France, Corsica and minor coastal islands included
Overseas regions: Guadeloupe, Martinique, Réunion, Mayotte and French Guiana
Overseas collectivities: French Polynesia, Saint Barthélemy, Saint Martin and Saint Pierre and Miquelon and Wallis and Futuna

The overseas territory of French Southern and Antarctic Lands divided in five districts: Kerguelen Islands, St. Paul and Amsterdam islands, Crozet Islands, Adélie Land and the Scattered Islands in the Indian Ocean
The special collectivity of New Caledonia
Clipperton Island under direct authority of the Minister of Overseas France  The European territory of France covers
An oceanic climate in the west and northwest: warm (but not hot) summers and cool (but not cold) winters
A semi-continental climate in the northeast: hot summers and cold winters
A Mediterranean climate in the south and southeast: hot summers and mild winters

A mountain (or alpine) climate in the Alps, the Pyrenees, the Massif Central, the Jura and the Vosges: mild summers and cold winters Except in the south which has generally dry summers, rain is evenly dispersed throughout the year in the rest of the country.  In the overseas regions, there are three broad types of climate:
A tropical climate in most overseas regions: high constant temperature throughout the year with a dry and a wet season
An equatorial climate in French Guiana: high constant temperature throughout the year with even precipitation throughout the year
A subpolar climate in Saint Pierre and Miquelon and in most of the French Southern and Antarctic Lands: short mild summers and long very cold winters
